1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What is a Bill?

A Bill is a proposed law presented in Parliament.
When passed and approved → becomes an Act.

🔵 Types of Bills
1️⃣ Ordinary Bill
Can be introduced in either House
Needs approval of both Houses
President can:
Approve
Return
Withhold
🔴 2️⃣ Money Bill (Article 110)

Deals with:

Taxation
Borrowing
Government expenditure
Key Points:
Introduced only in Lok Sabha
Requires President’s prior recommendation
Rajya Sabha can only delay for 14 days
Speaker decides whether it is a Money Bill

📌 Very important UPSC area.

🔵 3️⃣ Financial Bill
Similar to Money Bill but broader
Can be introduced in Lok Sabha only
🔴 4️⃣ Constitutional Amendment Bill
Amends Constitution
Special majority required
President cannot return it
🔹 Law Making Process
Step 1: First Reading
Introduction of bill
Step 2: Second Reading
Detailed discussion
Committee stage
Step 3: Third Reading
Final voting
Step 4: Other House
Same process repeated
Step 5: President’s Assent
Bill becomes law
🔹 Joint Sitting
If deadlock between houses
Called by President
Presided by Lok Sabha Speaker

📌 Used rarely.

🔹 Key Differences
Feature	Ordinary Bill	Money Bill
Introduction	Any House	Lok Sabha only
RS Power	Equal	Limited
President	Can return	Cannot return
